            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this student loan calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool models your student loans using standard amortization
                math and a simplified income-driven repayment (IDR) estimate. It
                is designed to be transparent: you can see the formulas,
                assumptions, and a full payment schedule.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Standard repayment formula</h3>
              <p>
                For a fixed-rate loan with a fixed term, the monthly payment is
                calculated using the standard amortization formula:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Monthly interest rate: \( r = \dfrac{\text{APR}}{12} \)</p>
                <p>Number of payments: \( n = \text{years} \times 12 \)</p>
                <p>Payment: \( P = \dfrac{r \cdot L}{1 - (1 + r)^{-n}} \)</p>
                <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">where:</p>
                <ul class="text-sm text-gray-700">
                  <li>\( L \) = loan balance (principal)</li>
                  <li>\( r \) = monthly interest rate (APR ÷ 12)</li>
                  <li>\( n \) = total number of monthly payments</li>
                  <li>\( P \) = fixed monthly payment</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Grace / in-school period</h3>
              <p>
                During the grace period you specify, the calculator assumes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>No payments are made.</li>
                <li>Interest accrues on the current balance each month.</li>
                <li>
                  Interest is capitalized (added to the balance) at the end of
                  the grace period.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This means starting repayment later increases your balance and
                total interest.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Extra payments and target payment</h3>
              <p>You can model two powerful strategies:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Extra monthly payment</strong> – a fixed amount added
                  to the required payment each month. It goes directly to
                  principal, shortening your payoff time and reducing interest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Target monthly budget</strong> – choose a payment
                  amount you can afford. The calculator estimates how many
                  months it will take to pay off the loan at that payment (as
                  long as it is above the minimum interest-only amount).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Income-driven repayment (IDR) estimate</h3>
              <p>
                Federal income-driven plans (like SAVE, PAYE, IBR) use your
                discretionary income and family size to determine a payment,
                often 5–20% of discretionary income. This calculator uses a
                simplified model:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Discretionary income ≈ annual income − 150% of a generic
                  poverty guideline for your family size.
                </li>
                <li>IDR payment ≈ (IDR % × discretionary income) ÷ 12.</li>
                <li>
                  Repayment term is assumed to be 20 years (240 payments).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If the IDR payment is lower than the interest that accrues each
                month, your balance may grow and you may see an estimated
                <strong>forgiveness amount</strong> at the end of the term. In
                reality, tax treatment and plan rules vary; always check
                official resources.
              </p>

              <h2>Interpreting your results</h2>
              <h3>Monthly payment</h3>
              <p>
                This is the amount you would pay each month under the selected
                plan. For standard repayment, it is fixed. For income-driven
                repayment, it is an estimate based on your income and family
                size.
              </p>

              <h3>Total interest paid</h3>
              <p>
                Total interest is the sum of all interest charges over the life
                of the loan. It depends on:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Your interest rate</li>
                <li>How long you take to repay</li>
                <li>Whether you make extra payments</li>
                <li>Any periods of non-payment where interest accrues</li>
