              <p>
                The calculator estimates how many months it will take to reach a
                zero balance and converts that into years and months. If you
                enter a target monthly payment, the term adjusts automatically.
              </p>

              <h2>Strategies to pay off student loans faster</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pay more than the minimum</strong> – even $25–$50
                  extra per month can save hundreds or thousands in interest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Refinance to a lower rate</strong> – if you have
                  strong credit and do not need federal protections, refinancing
                  may reduce your rate and payment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use windfalls wisely</strong> – tax refunds, bonuses,
                  or side income can be applied as lump-sum principal payments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Avoid unnecessary capitalization</strong> – when
                  possible, pay interest duringment or forbearance to
                  prevent it from being added to your principal.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is an educational tool and makes several
                simplifying assumptions:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Interest rate is fixed and does not change over time.</li>
                <li>
                  Payments are made on time every month with no missed or
                  partial payments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Income-driven repayment is modeled with generic poverty
                  guidelines and a fixed percentage of discretionary income.
                </li>
                <li>Tax implications of forgiveness are not modeled.</li>
              </ul>
