iscretionary income and family size to determine a payment, often 5–20% of discretionary income. This calculator uses a simplified model: Discretionary income ≈ annual income − 150% of a generic poverty guideline for your family size. IDR payment ≈ (IDR % × discretionary income) ÷ 12. Repayment term is assumed to be 20 years (240 payments). If the IDR payment is lower than the interest that accrues each month, your balance may grow and you may see an estimated forgiveness amount at the end of the term. In reality, tax treatment and plan rules vary; always check official resources. Interpreting your results Monthly payment This is the amount you would pay each month under the selected plan. For standard repayment, it is fixed. For income-driven repayment, it is an estimate based on your income and family size. Total interest paid Total interest is the sum of all interest charges over the life of the loan. It depends on: Your interest rate How long you take to repay Whether you make extra payments Any periods of non-payment where interest accrues Time to payoff and payoff date The calculator estimates how many months it will take to reach a zero balance and converts that into years and months. If you enter a target monthly payment, the term adjusts automatically. Strategies to pay off student loans faster Pay more than the minimum – even $25–$50 extra per month can save hundreds or thousands in interest. Refinance to a lower rate – if you have strong credit and do not need federal protections, refinancing may reduce your rate and payment. Use windfalls wisely – tax refunds, bonuses, or side income can be applied as lump-sum principal payments. Avoid unnecessary capitalization – when possible, pay interest duringment or forbearance to prevent it from being added to your principal. Limitations and assumptions This calculator is an educational tool and makes several simplifying assumptions: Interest rate is fixed and does not change over time. Payments are made on time every month with no missed or partial payments. Income-driven repayment is modeled with generic poverty guidelines and a fixed percentage of discretionary income. Tax implications of forgiveness are not modeled. Always confirm your actual payment amount, interest accrual, and eligibility for forgiveness or special programs with your loan servicer or a qualified financial professional. Student loan calculator FAQ How is my student loan payment calculated? For standard repayment, your payment is based on your principal balance, interest rate, and term using the standard amortization formula. The payment stays the same each month and is set so that your balance reaches zero at the end of the term, assuming on-time payments. Can I enter multiple student loans? Yes. Switch to the “Multiple loans” mode and add each loan with its own balance and interest rate. The calculator will combine them into a single weighted-average payment and schedule so you can see your total monthly obligation and payoff time. What happens if I pay extra each month? Extra payments are applied directly to principal after covering the required interest. This reduces your balance faster, which lowers future interest charges and shortens your payoff time. The calculator shows how much interest you can save with a given extra amount. Does this calculator support Public Service Loan Forgiveness (PSLF)? Not directly. PSLF has specific rules about qualifying loans, repayment plans, and employment. You can still use the income-driven estimate to get a sense of your monthly payment, but you should use the official federal loan simulator and your servicer’s tools for PSLF planning. Is refinancing my student loans always a good idea? No. Refinancing federal loans into a private loan can permanently remove access to income-driven repayment,ment, forbearance, and forgiveness programs. It may be worth considering if you have stable income, strong credit, and do not need federal protections, and if the new rate 