re made. Interest accrues on the current balance each month. Interest is capitalized (added to the balance) at the end of the grace period. This means starting repayment later increases your balance and total interest. 3. Extra payments and target payment You can model two powerful strategies: Extra monthly payment – a fixed amount added to the required payment each month. It goes directly to principal, shortening your payoff time and reducing interest. Target monthly budget – choose a payment amount you can afford. The calculator estimates how many months it will take to pay off the loan at that payment (as long as it is above the minimum interest-only amount). 4. Income-driven repayment (IDR) estimate Federal income-driven plans (like SAVE, PAYE, IBR) use your discretionary income and family size to determine a payment, often 5–20% of discretionary income. This calculator uses a simplified model: Discretionary income ≈ annual income − 150% of a generic poverty guideline for your family size. IDR payment ≈ (IDR % × discretionary income) ÷ 12. Repayment term is assumed to be 20 years (240 payments). If the IDR payment is lower than the interest that accrues each month, your balance may grow and you may see an estimated forgiveness amount at the end of the term. In reality, tax treatment and plan rules vary; always check official resources. Interpreting your results Monthly payment This is the amount you would pay each month under the selected plan. For standard repayment, it is fixed. For income-driven repayment, it is an estimate based on your income and family size. Total interest paid Total interest is the sum of all interest charges over the life of the loan. It depends on: Your interest rate How long you take to repay Whether you make extra payments Any periods of non-payment where interest accrues Time to payoff and payoff date The calculator estimates how many months it will take to reach a zero balance and converts that into years and months. If you enter a 